[1]
Date: Sat 20 Oct 2012
Source: The Australian [edited]
http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/hundreds-feared-exposed-to-tb/story-e6frg6nf-1226499648151


Doctors are scrambling to find hundreds of Queenslanders who may have unknowingly contracted a highly infectious strain of potentially lethal tuberculosis {TB}.

A homeless Aboriginal man -- recently diagnosed at Mossman, north of Cairns, after travelling around the state -- has been identified as the source of the outbreak. TB experts have sought to contact all GPs [general practitioners] in far north Queensland, warning the case could develop into an epidemic of "potentially catastrophic consequences" if not contained early.

However, Queensland's Chief Health Officer, Jeannette Young, yesterday [19 Oct 2012] said there was little risk to the general public, and only people who had come into close, sustained contact with the man were in danger of contracting the disease. "The biggest problem with him is we can't find the contacts (people he could have infected) without going through this process (of contacting doctors)," Dr Young said.

A total of 5 people are known to have caught tuberculosis -- which is spread through the air by coughing and sneezing -- from the man. The Weekend Australian has obtained a letter sent by Stephen Vincent, director of thoracic medicine in the Cairns and Hinterland Hospital and Health Service, to general practitioners in far north Queensland last month [September 2012], warning doctors of the "highly infectious case."

"This particular patient has travelled far and wide across the state and so far has infected a number of people including individuals in the Cairns district," Dr Vincent wrote. He advises doctors to pay special attention to high-risk patients -- those who are alcohol-dependent, homeless or indigenous -- and who are exhibiting symptoms such as unexplained weight loss, increasing night sweats and a worsening cough.

Usually, once someone is diagnosed with tuberculosis, doctors can visit their home and workplace to screen relatives and colleagues. Once identified, drug sensitive TB can be treated simply and effectively with antibiotics. However, in this case, the man had travelled widely and come in contact with dozens of people.

Dr Vincent, a TB expert speaking in his capacity as a private physician, said more than 200 people in the state could have been infected by the one man. "I would call it an epidemic of potentially catastrophic consequences if not contained early," he said.

"This is why we need to keep the QTBCC (Queensland Tuberculosis Control Centre) running." Dr Young said the Queensland government had "reassessed" its decision to disband the central Brisbane-based service and hand responsibility to the state's 17 new local health and hospital boards. She said while the centre would lose some administration staff and senior management, most of its clinical team would be embedded in Brisbane's Princess Alexandria Hospital.

"The idea was that all the (local) facilities would run their own TB service; now the decision has been made to keep a central unit at the PA that would provide the services for multiple (districts)," Dr Young said. "It's a reassessment that some facilities don't feel confident (to manage TB on their own)."

[Byline: Sarah Elks]

