[3]
Date: Sat 20 Oct 2012
Source: The Courier-Mail [edited]
http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/officials-reject-png-killer-tuberculosis-is-a-threat/story-e6freoof-1226499596455


Health officials have been accused of not doing enough to prevent an outbreak of a mutant strain of the killer lung disease tuberculosis spreading into north Queensland. But health authorities claim there is little to worry about.

The Courier-Mail yesterday [19 Oct 2012] revealed one of Australia's 1st cases of mutated XDR-TB (Extensively Drug-Resistant Tuberculosis) in a Papua New Guinean woman aged 20 years being treated in isolation at Cairns Base Hospital. Experts warn she is the 1st in a wave before the highly contagious, incurable, untreatable form of TB spreads. But Queensland's chief health officer Dr Jeannette Young yesterday played down the immediate threat. "Queensland is not at risk but certainly PNG [Papua New Guinea] is at risk, if we don't assist them as much as possible," she said.

Queensland taxpayers footed a AUD 32 million [USD 33 064 000] bill for the treatment for tuberculosis of about 100 Papua New Guineans over the past 2 years, with 92 patients handed back by Queensland Health in June -- 65 of them fully treated.

Health Minister Lawrence Springborg's office said that despite being an international matter, the Commonwealth did not fully fund health services to PNG nationals. The disagreement means Queensland must accept a Project Agreement by June or risk losing AUD 8.1 million [USD 8 369 325] in Commonwealth funding. Senate Estimates heard on Thursday that of AusAID's AUD 104 million [USD 107 458 000] allocation to the PNG health sector, only AUD 5.8 million [USD 5 992 850] was for programs relating to tuberculosis, of which PNG has the world's highest infection rate. Opposition Parliamentary Secretary Teresa Gambaro said: "PNG is our nearest neighbour we need to be doing more."

